      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Memory leaks in Python, especially when dealing with iterative processing, often happen because you're accidentally holding onto references to large objects from previous iterations. It's like a group of very greedy, slow-moving goblins who keep hoarding shiny pebbles from every batch you process, never letting go of the old ones!\n\nTo check for this, you can use system monitoring tools like `htop` or the built-in `resource` module (though platform-specific monitoring is often easier). You should monitor the Resident Set Size (RSS) of your Python process *before* the loop starts, *during* each iteration, and *after* the loop finishes. If the RSS keeps climbing steadily without dropping back down between chunks, you've got a memory leak.\n\nMake sure that inside your loop, any variables holding intermediate results are reassigned or explicitly set to `None` after you're done with them for that specific chunk. Don't let old DataFrames or large lists linger in scope if you don't need them anymore. This forces Python's garbage collector to clean up the old, unused memory chunks, keeping your footprint tight.\n\nAlso, if you are passing the chunk data into another function, ensure that",
